{"key":"processedPost-8499194","value":{"id":8499194,"first":8498822,"last":8506846,"when":1212931898,"utime":"06/08/08 04:31 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I *can* spawn to straight coir, but RR (at least at one point) recommended not doing that</blockquote><br />Actually, I was the first person around here, or any of the boards for that matter, to recommend coir as a substrate, back in '03 or '04.&nbsp; Before that, it was thought that coir was only suitable as a casing material, with 'no nutes'.&nbsp; My experiments showed it to be the equal of horse manure for growing certain species of mushrooms.<br />As with any substrate material, coir will benefit from the addition of gypsum.&nbsp; Coffee grinds are also a great addition, but coir can and has been used by itself with great results.&nbsp; Another great addition is vermiculite at around ten to twenty percent by volume.&nbsp; The vermiculite provides a moisture reservoir, and it also somehow serves as a pinset enhancer.&nbsp; I don't know how or why other than speculation, but bulk substrates including coir tend to pin better with a bit of verm added.<br />RR"}}